Levels of testing:
                 Unit Testing
                 Integration Testing
                 System Testing
                 Acceptance Testing
Unit Testing:
                 Tests individual units or components of the application
                 Performed mainly by developers
                 Focuses on internal logic and code correctness
                 Uses white-box testing techniques
                 Helps in early detection of defects, reducing cost
Integration Testing:
                 Tests interaction between integrated modules
                 Performed after unit testing
                 Focuses on data flow and interface issues
                 Can be done using top-down, bottom-up, or hybrid approaches
                 Detects defects related to module communication
System Testing
                 Tests the complete and integrated system
                 Performed by testers/QA team
                 Uses black-box testing techniques
                 Validates both functional and non-functional requirements
                 Conducted in an environment similar to production
Acceptance Testing (UAT)
                 Confirms system meets business and user requirements
                 Performed by end users or clients
                 Conducted after system testing
                 Focuses on real-world business scenarios
                 Determines final approval before release
